2.4 New Variables Creation

b). New Variable: total_delivery_duration
# `total_delivery_duration`: The aim of this study is to investigate the factors influencing the total delivery duration and develop a predictive model to enhance the accuracy of forecasting delivery times to customers. To enhance the predictive modeling performance in the dataset, the target variable total_delivery_duration was created by subtracting the created_at timestamp from the actual_delivery_time.
# Convert character strings to POSIXct objects
DoorDash1$created_at <- as.POSIXct(DoorDash1$created_at, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")
DoorDash1$actual_delivery_time <- as.POSIXct(DoorDash1$actual_delivery_time, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")

total_delivery_seconds <- difftime(DoorDash1$actual_delivery_time, DoorDash1$created_at, units = "secs")

# Convert total delivery duration to minutes (rounded to 2 decimal places)
DoorDash1$total_delivery_duration <- round(as.numeric(total_delivery_seconds) / 60, 2)
c). New Variable: busy_dashers_ratio
# `busy_dashers_ratio`: This variable indicates the ratio of busy dashers to the total dashers on shift, where a higher ratio implies a lower availability of dashers, potentially increasing delivery times. This is directly related to the efficiency of deliveries.
DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio <- round((DoorDash1$total_busy_dashers / DoorDash1$total_onshift_dashers),2)
# Replace negative values and positive infinity with NaN
DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio[DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio < 0 | is.infinite(DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio)] <- NaN
class(DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio)
## [1] "numeric"
# Remove rows with NaN values in the busy_dashers_ratio column
DoorDash1 <- DoorDash1[complete.cases(DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio), ]

# Check if there are any NaN values left in the column
any(is.nan(DoorDash1$busy_dashers_ratio))
## [1] FALSE
d). New Variable: estimate_non_preparation_duration
# Analyze and predict the time portion of the entire food delivery process to determine whether it impacts the total_delivery_duration or not. estimate_non_preparation_duration includes the time estimated for the restaurant to receive the order from DoorDash and the estimated travel time between the store and the consumer.
DoorDash1$estimate_non_preparation_duration <- DoorDash1$estimated_order_place_duration + DoorDash1$estimated_store_to_consumer_driving_duration
e). New Variable: percent_distinct_item_of_total
# `percent_distinct_item_of_total`: provides an indication of the diversity of items within each order. Higher values of percent_distinct_item_of_total indicate greater diversity in the items ordered within each order. 
DoorDash1$percent_distinct_item_of_total <- round((DoorDash1$num_distinct_items / DoorDash1$total_items) * 100, 2)
f) . New Variable: price_range max price - min price
# `price_range`: The difference between the highest and lowest item prices in an order. If there are items in the order with a large price difference, it may mean that the preparation of these items is very different. For example, more expensive items may require a more complex preparation process or more advanced ingredients, while cheaper items may be relatively simple and quick. As a result, orders with a wide price range may require different lead times and resource allocations.
DoorDash1$price_range = DoorDash1$max_item_price - DoorDash1$min_item_price
DoorDash1 <- DoorDash1[DoorDash1$price_range > 0, ]

2.5 Handling outliers

# Removing outliers can reduce the variability and information in the data and introduce bias or distortion. Therefore, only remove outliers if they are certainty irrelevant or erroneous, and that they will not affect the outcome or the interpretation of the data [1].
# Convert variables to numeric
DoorDash1$total_items <- as.numeric(DoorDash1$total_items)
DoorDash1$subtotal <- as.numeric(DoorDash1$subtotal)
DoorDash1$num_distinct_items <- as.numeric(DoorDash1$num_distinct_items)
DoorDash1$min_item_price <- as.numeric(DoorDash1$min_item_price)
DoorDash1$max_item_price <- as.numeric(DoorDash1$max_item_price)

# Function to remove outliers using IQR method
remove_outliers <- function(data, var) {
  q1 <- quantile(data[[var]], 0.25)
  q3 <- quantile(data[[var]], 0.75)
  iqr <- q3 - q1
  lower_bound <- q1 - 3 * iqr
  upper_bound <- q3 + 3 * iqr
  data <- data[data[[var]] >= lower_bound & data[[var]] <= upper_bound, ]
  return(data)
}

# Apply the function to remove outliers for each variable
for (var in variables_to_check) {
  DoorDash1 <- remove_outliers(DoorDash1, var)
}

# Variables weekend and time_peak are created based on the analysis of order creation time and dates. According to the figures above, there was a high peak in placing orders on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays. Furthermore, a high peak in placing orders was identified between 6 AM to 9 AM, 11 AM to 1 PM, and 5 PM to 8 PM. The purpose of creating these new variables is to determine whether they are significant factors impacting total_delivery_duration or not.

6. Dummy Variables Creation: market_id, store_primary_category, order_protocol

# Convert 'market_id' to factor to ensure correct encoding
DoorDash1$market_id <- as.factor(DoorDash1$market_id)

# Create dummy variables for 'market_id'
market_id_dummies <- model.matrix(~ market_id - 1, data = DoorDash1)

# Convert the result to a data frame
market_id_dummies_df <- as.data.frame(market_id_dummies)

# Rename the columns to indicate the market IDs
colnames(market_id_dummies_df) <- paste0("market_id_", levels(DoorDash1$market_id))

# Merge the dummy variables with the original data frame
DoorDash1 <- cbind(DoorDash1, market_id_dummies_df)

DoorDash1$store_primary_category <- as.factor(DoorDash1$store_primary_category)
